The clean_names() function takes the vector of names from a data set and alters the names to be read and understood easier. It is useful because proper names describe the data and result in less reliance on the codebook.

Question 3

Perform an initial split of the data. Stratify by the outcome variable. You can choose a proportion to use. Verify that your training and test sets have the desired number of observations.

set.seed(777)
pokemon_split <- initial_split(pokemon, strata = "type_1", prop = 0.80)
pokemon_train <- training(pokemon_split)
pokemon_test <- testing(pokemon_split)

Next, use v-fold cross-validation on the training set. Use 5 folds. Stratify the folds by type_1 as well. Hint: Look for a strata argument. Why might stratifying the folds be useful?

pokemon_fold <- vfold_cv(pokemon, v = 5, strata = "type_1")

Question 4

Set up a recipe to predict type_1 with legendary, generation, sp_atk, attack, speed, defense, hp, and sp_def. Dummy-code legendary and generation; Center and scale all predictors.

pokemon_recipe <- recipe(type_1 ~ legendary + generation + sp_atk + attack + speed + defense + hp + sp_def, pokemon_train) %>% 
  step_dummy(legendary) %>% 
  step_dummy(generation) %>% 
  step_center(all_predictors()) %>%
  step_scale(all_predictors())

Question 5

We’ll be fitting and tuning an elastic net, tuning penalty and mixture (use multinom_reg with the glmnet engine).

multi_recipe <- 
  recipe(formula = type_1 ~ ., data = pokemon_train) %>% 
  step_novel(all_nominal_predictors()) %>% 
  step_dummy(all_nominal_predictors()) %>% 
  step_zv(all_predictors()) %>% 
  step_normalize(all_predictors())
multi_spec <- multinom_reg(mixture = tune(), penalty = tune()) %>%
  set_mode("classification") %>%
  set_engine("glmnet")

Set up this model and workflow. Create a regular grid for penalty and mixture with 10 levels each; mixture should range from 0 to 1. For this assignment, we’ll let penalty range from -5 to 5 (it’s log-scaled).

multi_fit <- fit(multi_spec, type_1 ~ ., data = pokemon_train)
## Warning in glmnet::glmnet(x = maybe_matrix(x), y = y, alpha = ~tune(), family =
## "multinomial"): alpha >1; set to 1
multi_workflow <- workflow() %>% 
  add_recipe(multi_recipe) %>% 
  add_model(multi_spec)
reg_grid <- grid_regular(mixture(range = c(0,1)), penalty(range = c(-5, 5)), levels = 10)
reg_grid

Question 9

In the 2020-2021 season, Stephen Curry, an NBA basketball player, made 337 out of 801 three point shot attempts (42.1%). Use bootstrap resampling on a sequence of 337 1’s (makes) and 464 0’s (misses). For each bootstrap sample, compute and save the sample mean (e.g. bootstrap FG% for the player). Use 1000 bootstrap samples to plot a histogram of those values. Compute the 99% bootstrap confidence interval for Stephen Curry’s “true” end-of-season FG% using the quantile function in R. Print the endpoints of this interval.

library(boot)
set <- c(rep(0, times = 464), rep(1, times = 337))
mean(set)
## [1] 0.4207241
resample <- sample(set, replace = TRUE)
mean(resample)
## [1] 0.4294632
out <- replicate(1000, {sample_set <- sample(set, replace = TRUE)
  mean(sample_set)})
hist(out)

bstrap <- c()
for (i in 1:1000){bsample <- sample(set, replace=T)
  bestimate <- mean(bsample)
  bstrap <- c(bstrap,bestimate)}
quantile(bstrap,.99)
##       99% 
## 0.4619351
quantile(bstrap,.01)
##        1% 
## 0.3795256
"(0.3820225,0.4594382)"
## [1] "(0.3820225,0.4594382)"
